{{unreferenced|date=May 2016}}
'''Decapping''' (decapsulation) or '''delidding''' of an [[integrated circuit]] is the process of removing the protective cover of a microchip so that the contained [[Die (integrated circuit)|die]] is revealed for [[visual inspection]] of the micro circuitry imprinted on the die. This process is typically done in order to debug a manufacturing problem with the chip, or possibly to copy information from the device. Modern integrated circuits can be encapsulated in plastic, [[ceramic]], or epoxy.

Decapping is usually carried out by chemical etching of the covering, laser cutting, or mechanical removal of the cover using a [[Milling (machining)|milling machine]]. The process can be either destructive or non-destructive.

