{{short description|University research center for the study of Digital History}} {{third-party|date=March 2017}} {{Use mdy dates|date=September 2018}} {{Infobox university | name = Roy Rosenzweig Center for History and New Media | image_name = | city = [[Fairfax County, Virginia|Fairfax County]] | state = [[Virginia]] | country = [[United States]] | affiliations = [[George Mason University]] | established = 1994 | website = [http://chnm.gmu.edu/ chnm.gmu.edu] }}
'''Roy Rosenzweig Center for History and New Media''' ('''RRCHNM'''), formerly the '''Center for History and New Media''' ('''CHNM''') is a research institution in the [[George Mason University]] in [[Fairfax County, Virginia]] specializing in history and information technology. It was established by [[Roy Rosenzweig]] in 1994 to research and use [[digital media]] and [[information technology]] in [[history|historical]] research, education, digital tools and resources, [[digital preservation]], and outreach.
== Digital preservation == [[File:Roy Rosenzweig Center for History and New Media F.jpg|thumb|right|Center for History and New Media Offices]] Following the [[September 11, 2001 attacks]], the Center for History and New Media in partnership with the American Social History Project at the [[City University of New York]] organized the September 11 Digital Archive with funding from the [[Alfred P. Sloan]] Foundation.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://911digitalarchive.org/about | title = About the September 11 Digital Archive | publisher = 911digitalarchive.org | date = September 11, 2001 | accessdate = December 12, 2017 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180419133447/http://911digitalarchive.org/about | archive-date = April 19, 2018 | dead-url = no
}}</ref> With the September 11 Digital Archive, CHNM and ASHP utilized electronic media to collect, preserve, and present the past, with a digital repository of material including more than 150,000 first-hand accounts, emails, images, and other digital materials. This project has inspired a new project, the Hurricane Digital Memory Bank, which is collecting the stories and digital artefacts related to the [[Hurricane Katrina]], [[Hurricane Rita|Rita]], and [[Hurricane Wilma|Wilma]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://hurricanearchive.org/about/ | title = About the Hurricane Digital Memory Bank | publisher = Hurricanearchive.org | accessdate = August 7, 2010 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180419135931/http://hurricanearchive.org/about/ | archive-date = April 19, 2018 | dead-url = no
}}</ref> CHNM continues to explore methods, tools, and technologies for archiving and preserving information, data, and documents digitally.
== Educational resources == The Center for History and New Media worked in partnership with the American Social History Project (ASHP) at the City University of New York, to develop an online resource directed at [[History of the United States|American History]] teachers, along with online resources about the [[French Revolution]]. More recent projects have focused on developing online educational resources about [[World History]], and a project on historical thinking, in partnership with the [[Smithsonian Institution]]’s [[National Museum of American History]]. CHNM is also involved with educational outreach with teachers in [[Virginia]] school districts.
CHNM has also developed a number of online databases and other resources for historians and history teachers, including a listing of 1,200 history departments worldwide, a practical guide to Digital History, a collection of essays on history and new media. Another online database is Making the History of 1989, which chronicles the fall of [[communism]] in [[Eastern Europe]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://chnm.gmu.edu/1989/ | title = Making the History of 1989 | publisher = Chnm.gmu.edu | accessdate = August 7, 2010 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110628175958/http://chnm.gmu.edu/1989/ | archive-date = June 28, 2011 | dead-url = no
}}</ref> Created in collaboration with the [[German Historical Institute]] and the [[National Endowment for the Humanities]], the 1989 Project is powered by CHNM's [[Omeka]] software, and includes resources for teachers and students, ranging from lesson plans to an [[archive]] of [[primary source]] materials.
CHNM collaborated with the [[Jewish Women's Archive]] on Katrina's Jewish Voices, a virtual archive of stories, images, and reflections about the New Orleans and Gulf Coast Jewish communities before and after Hurricane Katrina.
== Software resources == [[File:Roy Rosenzweig Center for History and New Media A - Stierch.jpg|thumb|right|Community area of the center]] CHNM is responsible for the development of two notable [[Open-source software|open source]] software projects: [[Zotero]] and [[Omeka]]. [[Zotero]] is [[reference management software]] which is used by [[academia|academics]] to read and cite the [[Academic publishing|academic literature]]. [[Omeka]] is a [[content management system]] that uses the [[Dublin Core]] metadata standard to build digital collections and publish digital exhibits. Both projects are free, and reflect CHNM's dedication to democratizing the practice of history.
The Center for History and New Media also distributes a set of free additional digital tools for historians and teachers, including Web Scrapbook, Survey Builder, Scribe (a note taking application designed with historians in mind), Poll Builder, H-Bot (an automated historical fact finder), and Syllabus Finder, which allows you to find and compare syllabi from thousands of universities and colleges on any topic, using the [[Google]] search engine.
In 2017, with financial support of the [[Andrew W. Mellon Foundation]], CHNM released Tropy,<ref>{{cite web | last1 = Jackson | first1 = Zoë | title = Research Clutter: A New App Helps Create Order Out of Disorder | url = https://www.historians.org/publications-and-directories/perspectives-on-history/april-2018/research-clutter-a-new-app-helps-create-order-out-of-disorder | website = Perspectives | publisher = American Historical Association | accessdate = August 14, 2018 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180819000816/https://www.historians.org/publications-and-directories/perspectives-on-history/april-2018/research-clutter-a-new-app-helps-create-order-out-of-disorder | archive-date = August 19, 2018 | dead-url = no
}}</ref> a [[free and open-source software|free and open-source]] desktop [[knowledge organization]] application to manage and describe photographs of research materials.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://tropy.org/blog/tropy-1-0-released/ | title = Tropy 1.0 released | date = October 24, 2017 | work = ''tropy.org'' | access-date = September 27, 2018 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180912010817/https://tropy.org/blog/tropy-1-0-released/ | archive-date = September 12, 2018 | dead-url = no
}}</ref>
== Scholarship == Projects like Zotero provide tools for historians to research and analyze the past. But will digital media change the nature of scholarly argument, communication, and publication? In order to encourage experimentation in this arena, American Quarterly in collaboration with the American Studies Crossroads Project and CHNM organized an experiment in hypertext publishing.<ref>{{Cite journal | last = Rosenzweig | first = Roy | date = June 1, 1999 | title = Crashing the System? Hypertext and Scholarship on American Culture | url = https://muse.jhu.edu/article/2395 | journal = American Quarterly
| volume = 51 | issue = 2 | pages = 237–246 | doi = 10.1353/aq.1999.0029 | issn = 1080-6490 | access-date = September 27, 2018 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180428131102/https://muse.jhu.edu/article/2395 | archive-date = April 28, 2018 | dead-url = no
}}</ref> Four essays, covering such diverse topics as photos, as legal evidence, the [[Spanish–American War]] in film, early comic strips, and [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]], offer contrasting approaches to using digital media for scholarly presentations.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://chnm.gmu.edu/aq | title = Hypertext Scholarship in American Studies | publisher = Chnm.gmu.edu | accessdate = August 7, 2010 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100714074134/http://chnm.gmu.edu/aq/ | archive-date = July 14, 2010 | dead-url = no
}}</ref>
Imaging the French Revolution is another experiment in digital scholarship. In a series of essays, seven scholars analyze forty-two images of crowds and crowd violence in the French Revolution. Offering the most relevant examples and comments from an on-line forum, those same scholars consider issues of interpretation, methodology, and the impact of digital media on scholarship.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://chnm.gmu.edu/revolution/imaging | title = Imaging the French Revolution | publisher = Chnm.gmu.edu | accessdate = August 7, 2010 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20101006035114/http://chnm.gmu.edu/revolution/imaging/ | archive-date = October 6, 2010 | dead-url = no
}}</ref>
Finally, Interpreting the [[United States Declaration of Independence|Declaration of Independence]] by Translation<ref>{{cite web | url = http://chnm.gmu.edu/declaration | title = Interpreting the Declaration of Independence by Translation | publisher = Chnm.gmu.edu | accessdate = August 7, 2010 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100601184421/http://chnm.gmu.edu/declaration/ | archive-date = June 1, 2010 | dead-url = no
}}</ref> is a roundtable of historians brought together to discuss the translation and reception of the Declaration of Independence in Japan, Mexico, Russia, China, Poland, Italy, Germany, Spain, and Israel. In addition to these reflections, the site includes actual translations of the Declaration into several different languages and "re-translations" back into English to illustrate the effects of translation on how a key historical document has been understood.
== Public outreach == CHNM has also developed some projects with an explicit focus on broad, public audiences. [[Gulag]]: Many Days, Many Lives<ref>{{cite web | url = http://gulaghistory.org | title = Gulag: Many Days, Many Lives &#124; Home | publisher = Gulaghistory.org | accessdate = August 7, 2010 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180430155402/http://gulaghistory.org/ | archive-date = April 30, 2018 | dead-url = yes
}}</ref> is a web-based exhibit funded by NEH and being developed in collaboration with the [[Gulag Museum]] in [[Perm, Russia]], will provide a multifaceted consideration of the human struggle for survival in the Gulag, the brutal and often lethal Soviet system of forced labor [[concentration camp]]s. [[History News Network]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://chnm.gmu.edu/hnn | title = History News Network | publisher = Chnm.gmu.edu | accessdate = August 7, 2010 | deadurl = yes | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080829161808/http://chnm.gmu.edu/hnn | archivedate = August 29, 2008 | df = }}</ref> features articles, placing current events in historical perspective, written by historians of all political persuasions.
== Name change == On April 15, 2011, the Center for History and New Media became the Roy Rosenzweig Center for History and New Media, in memory of its founder.
